               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360509-name-218" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-218" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-218" type="surname" value="DALE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-218" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM DALE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am servant to Benjamin Brasier, a chimney-sweeper, the prisoner was there too—we slept together. At five o'clock in the</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183605090042"></xptr>
               <p>morning, on the 12th of April, my master called him up to go to work—he chucked his own shoes into the soot-shed—he did not go to work, but ran away, and was found over Stratford-bridge, near the church—these are the shoes I had left by my bed.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner</hi>. I asked him to lend me his shoes to go to work, and he did. <hi rend="italic">Witness</hi> No., I did not.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360509-name-219" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-219" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-219" type="surname" value="BRAZIER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-219" type="given" value="BENJAMIN"></interp>BENJAMIN BRAZIER</persName>
                  </hi>. I called the prisoner at five o'clock, to go down to Bromley—when I came down, I found him gone—I went to his shed to look for his tools, none were there, and his shoes and cap were thrown into the shed—I went after him to Stratford, and caught him before he came to Stratford-bridge—he was running by himself—he had a climbing-cap on his head, and Dale's shoes were on his feet—I said, "You are a nice gentleman, "he said, "<hi rend="italic">Bill</hi> lent them to me"—"Let go my collar"—I let him go, and he walked to the foot of Bow-bridge.</p>
